IE 360 Homework 2 - Selin Coşkun¶

Introduction¶

In this study, the quarterly gasoline sales data (in 1000 m^3) from 2000 to 2006 sold by a major distributor is given. There are some variables that can explain the sales numbers given in the data set. The variables in the data set are shown and explained below:

UGS: Unleaded gasoline sale in a given quarter, RNUV: An index indicating the rate of new unleaded gasoline using vehicles being added to the traffic in a quarter, PU: Average price (adjusted with an index) of a liter of unleaded gasoline in a quarter, PG: Average price (adjusted with an index) of a liter of diesel gasoline in a quarter, NUGV: Number of unleaded gasoline using vehicles in the traffic, NDGV: Number of diesel gasoline using vehicles in the traffic (per 1000 people), GNPA: Agriculture component of Gross National Product (adjusted with an index), GNPC: Commerce component of Gross National Product (adjusted with an index), GNP: Grand total for GNP (agriculture, commerce and other components total).

The main aim in this study is to forecast the unleaded gasoline sales in 2007 for 4 quarters within. In order to do that, firstly, some plots will be drawn and examined, stationarity of the data will be questioned, autocorrelation functions of the time series data UGS will also be examined. Secondly, trend, seasonality and residual values will be added to the data set as additional variables. After that, models will be created for the time series data and predictions will be implemented according to the best model found.

Plots to Examine Data Visually and Analytically¶

In [5]:
options(repr.plot.width = 20, repr.plot.height =8)
ggplot(gasoline[1:28,], aes(x = Quarter, y = Unleaded.Gasoline.Sale..UGS.)) + 
geom_bar(stat='identity', aes(fill=Quarter))+
ggtitle("Bar Plot of Quarterly Unleaded Gasoline Sales") + theme(plot.title = element_text(size=30)) +
xlab("Quarter")+
ylab("UGS")

From the quarterly bar plot of unleaded gasoline sales (UGS), it can be stated that the data is not stationary. The reason why it can be said that is the sales data seems to have seasonality with period 4 and a decreasing trend over time.

In [6]:
ts = ts(gasoline[,c(2:10)],freq= 4,start = c(2000,1),end = c(2006,4))
ts.plot(ts[,'Unleaded.Gasoline.Sale..UGS.'],xlab = "Years",ylab = "UGS", main = "Quarterly Unleaded Gasoline Sales 2000-2006",col= rep("mediumorchid3",4))
index = 2000 + c(0:27) / 4
points(index, gasoline$Unleaded.Gasoline.Sale..UGS.[1:28], col = "mediumorchid4", pch=19)

In the above code, the data is converted to time series data, and then plotted. The non-stationarity of the data can also be derived from the ts.plot because despite the varience seems approximately constant, the mean of the data seems to vary over time.

In [7]:
tsdisplay(ts[,1],lag.max = 12,main = 'Unleaded Gasoline Sales')

Above, the plot of the time series is shown with the autocorrelation functions. The seasonality of the time series data with period 4 can be verified with the ACF plot because the autocorrelation with lag 4 is higher than the treshold value. Additionally, the data points are correlated with their lag 4 values more than their lag 8 values, more higher than their lag 12 values. This demonstrates that the successive years are more correlated than the other years.

Modelling¶

In this part of the study, some linear regression models are constructed in order to forecast 2007's gasoline sales. In each of the various models, some variables are added or removed in the way of findind the best model that will give accurate results. The quality of the model is measured and justified by the Adjusted R^2 output.

Conclusion¶

In this homework, first, the given data including the unleaded gasoline sales is prepared by deleting the spaces between numbers, converting the variables to numeric data and converting the whole data set into time series data. After preparing the data, some plots are drawn and the non-stationarity, seasonality and trend of the data is observed by these plots. In addition to these plots, the ACF plot is also drawn in order to verify the seasonality and to observe the correlation between data points. After that, data is rearranged as the trend and seasonality components of the data set are included in the data and converted into time series again. As the next part of the study, in order to forecast the 2007's sales, models are constructed and evaluated first considering their Adjusted R^2, secondly by evaluating their p-values and the distribution, the mean and the varience of their residuals. In the models, the most significant variables are taken into consideration and the insignificant variables are excluded from the model one by one. Afterh that, the residuals of the best model found are included in the last model as a new variable, and the data set is rearranged again as it is converted to time series data again. Lastly, the last and best model is used in predicting the sales in 2007, and the corresponding sales numbers for quarter 1, 2, 3 and 4 are 692124.971128693, 809121.713875698, 998937.281457814, 764388.546338691 respectively. The plot that shows the real values and the predicted values for the unleaded gasoline sales between 2000 and 2007 is given below.
